\begin_layout Subsubsection
The production function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Gross output 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is produced with capital equipment, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{iM}$
\end_inset

, energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, labor, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, capital structures (buildings) 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{iB}$
\end_inset

, and intermediate inputs 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
All inputs except intermediate inputs enter production in effective units
 which include factor utilization and in the case of labor, net of hiring
 costs.
 Effective capital inputs are denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{iM,s,t-1}^{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{iB,s,t-1}^{u}$
\end_inset

 (superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 for utilization).
 Capital stocks are subject to a one period time to build which implies
 they are fixed in the short run (current period) although they can be used
 with varying intensity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We write the general production function in sector 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
KELBR_{s,t}=Q\left(K_{iM,s,t-1}^{u},E_{sp,t},L_{s,t},K_{iB,s,t-1}^{u},R_{sp,t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

In what follows sector and time indices are omitted when that does not affect
 exposition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The CES tree
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Production inputs generate output through a CES nest structure where superscript
s 
\begin_inset Formula $K,E,L,B,R$
\end_inset

 denote equipment capital, energy, labor, structures, and intermediate inputs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\size small
\begin_inset Formula $\xymatrix{KELBR\left(KELB,R\right)\ar@{-}[dr]\ar@{-}[d]\\
KELB\left(KEL,K_{iB}\right)\ar@{-}[dr]\ar@{-}[d] & R\\
KEL\left(KE,L\right)\ar@{-}[dr]\ar@{-}[d] & K_{iB}\\
KE\left(K_{iM},E\right)\ar@{-}[dr]\ar@{-}[d] & L\\
K_{iM} & E
}
$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
CES cost minimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal demand for inputs is obtained from solving a sequence of cost
 minimization problems at every level in the tree.
 As an example, the problem at the bottom branch of the upper tree is to
 minimize total cost 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{KE}KE=p^{K}K^{u}+p^{E}E$
\end_inset

 subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $KE=CES\left(K^{u},E\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The solution to this problem is well known and yields the following objects
 which, with the necessary extensions and appropriate indexing, translate
 appropriately to all levels of the tree:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is easy to show that the CES structure also captures zero elasticities
 of substitution.
 The demand functions, constraint, and CES price all go through, while we
 never make use of the production function, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{KEL}=min(KE,L/\mu^{L})$
\end_inset

, and of course there are no derivatives but instead optimality implies
 
\begin_inset Formula $KE=L/\mu^{L}=KEL$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{Output} & \Rightarrow & KE=\left[\left(1-\omega^{E}\right)^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\left(K^{u}\right)^{\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}}+\omega^{E}{}^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\left(E\right)^{\frac{\eta-1}{\eta}}\right]^{\frac{\eta}{\eta-1}}\\
\\
\text{Derivative} & \Rightarrow & \frac{\partial KE}{\partial E}=\left[\omega^{E}\frac{KE}{E}\right]^{\frac{1}{\eta}}\\
\\
\text{Demand/F.O.C.} & \Rightarrow & E=\omega^{E}KE\left(\frac{P^{KE}}{p^{E}}\right)^{\eta}\\
\\
\text{CES Price} & \Rightarrow & P^{KE}=\left[\left(1-\omega^{E}\right)\left(p^{K}\right)^{1-\eta}+\omega^{E}\left(p^{E}\right)^{1-\eta}\right]^{\frac{1}{1-\eta}}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In these equations the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{j}$
\end_inset

 are share parameters.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of substitution between the two inputs.
 The input prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{j}$
\end_inset

(not the CES prices 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

) are user costs except for intermediate goods where it is a CES aggregate
 of spot prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One detail to mention is that, although we show it explicitly here, the
 production function is never used in the numerical solution to the problem.
 Much like the utility function in the household problem, only its derivatives
 are ever needed, and they enter the problem through the demand functions
 shown above.
 The problem is solved using only the demand functions and the constraint
 in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{KE}KE=p^{K}K+p^{E}E$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving all the problems in the tree requires knowing the correct prices
 of every input.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intermediate inputs and energy in production as well as capital investments
 are sourced from many production sectors, both domestic and foreign, in
 exactly the same way as all other demand components.
 The prices of intermediate inputs and investments are derived in input/output
 chapter.
 Firms pay same the wage pr.
 unit of labor, but user costs will generally differ between sectors due
 to differences in labor adjustment costs etc.
 The user cost of labor is derived in the labor market chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finding the correct input prices of capital (and labor) requires solving
 a dynamic, forward-looking, optimization problem.
 We look at the user cost of capital in the next subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamic optimization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Dynamic-optimization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section derives the user cost of capital.
 All variables and parameters in the problem generally have a sub-index
 
\begin_inset Formula $(k,s,t)$
\end_inset

 â€“ that is over investment/capital type, sector and time.
 In this section, this index will be truncated to only 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, unless otherwise explicitly stated.
 Given eight different private sectors and two types of capital, MAKRO has
 16 appropriately indexed versions of the variables and equations described.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All capital stocks have a law of motion of the following form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{t}=\left(1-\delta_{t}\right)K_{t-1}+I_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the depreciation rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the investment flow.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Inventory investment is assumed to be proportional to net output: 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{invt,sp,t}=\mu_{sp,t}^{Invt}Y_{sp,t}$
\end_inset

.
 It does not accumulate or contribute to production.
 It is just a drain on resources in order to match the model with national
 accounts data, where it is small fraction of total spending (less than
 0.5 percent).
 Inventories are listed in the index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 which identifies the three types of investments (inventories, equipment,
 structures): 
\begin_inset Formula $i=\{iL,iM,iB\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capital stocks are subject to adjustment costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
AC_{t}=\frac{\gamma}{2}\left[\frac{K_{t}}{K_{t-1}}/\frac{K_{t-1}}{\overline{K}_{t-2}}-1\right]^{2}K_{t-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 parameter controls the severity of adjustment costs and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{K}_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the average capital stock in the sector.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We apply the same adjustment cost function to prices, wages, and capital
 stocks.
 In each case, we consider the object with two lags to be external to the
 optimizing agent.
 I.e.
 we do not take a derivative wrt.
 the effect two periods ahead.
 Internalizing this tertiary effect has made no practical difference in
 testing.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Branch AC_derivatives
inverted 0
status open

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
AC_{t+1}=\frac{\gamma}{2}\left[\frac{K_{t+1}}{K_{t}}/\frac{K_{t}}{\overline{K}_{t-1}}-1\right]^{2}K_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial AC_{t}}{\partial K_{t}}=\gamma\left[\frac{K_{t}}{K_{t-1}}/\frac{K_{t-1}}{\overline{K}_{t-2}}-1\right]\left[\frac{K_{t}}{K_{t-1}}/\frac{K_{t-1}}{\overline{K}_{t-2}}\right]\frac{K_{t-1}}{K_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial AC_{t+1}}{\partial K_{t}}=-2\gamma\left[\frac{K_{t+1}}{K_{t}}/\frac{K_{t}}{\overline{K}_{t-1}}-1\right]\left[\frac{K_{t+1}}{K_{t}}/\frac{K_{t}}{\overline{K}_{t-1}}\right]+\frac{1}{K_{t}}AC_{t+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial AC_{t+2}}{\partial\overline{K}_{t}}=\gamma\left[\frac{K_{t+2}}{K_{t+1}}/\frac{K_{t+1}}{\overline{K}_{t}}-1\right]\frac{K_{t+2}}{K_{t+1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capital stocks are fixed in the short run due to one period time to build,
 but they can be used with varying intensity 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The problem of optimal capital utilization is examined below.
 Adjustment and utilization costs as well as vacancy costs are not explicitly
 measured in the data, and are modeled as unobserved lost production.
 Adjustment costs are subtracted from gross production, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Gross and net output are related by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=A_{s,t}\left[KELBR_{t}-\sum_{k}AC{}_{k,t}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 identifies the type of capital good (equipment or structures).
 Note that we do not see the vacancy posting costs or labor utilization
 costs explicitly here, as they are modeled directly inside gross output
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and detailed in the labor market chapter.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 measures residual total factor productivity after labor-saving technological
 progress (embodied in the quantity of labor supplied by households), variable
 factor utilization, and adjustment costs in labor and capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Debt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model the debt issued by the firm as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{t}=\mu_{t}^{D}p_{t}^{I}K_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{D}$
\end_inset

 is a factor taken as given by the optimizing firm and which can be viewed
 as the result of an independent optimal corporate capital structure problem.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{D}$
\end_inset

 is then an expression of a modified Modigliani-Miller theorem.
 There is an implicit trade-off between bankruptcy risk and associated costs
 on one hand, and the gain from financing the firm at a lower rate on the
 other.
 Currently all firms in the model have the same constant debt factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{D}=0.4$
\end_inset

.
 This way of modeling debt mirrors the way mortgage debt is modeled on our
 household side of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are other reasons to link debt to the firm's capital stock.
 One significant component of firm debt is mortgage debt, which is closely
 related to (or collateralized by) the firm's capital stock.
 Corporate debt is also issued with various covenants (such as not allowing
 sales of installed capital), which serve as an indirect claim on the firm's
 equipment and structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The problem of the firm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For exposition purposes, we state the problem with a single capital stock
 rather than two, and we use only the time index on all variables.
 As we focus only on the optimal choice of capital, we also leave out many
 details of the labor input.
 The operating surplus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 in a period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{t} & =\left(1-\tau_{t}^{c}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
P_{t}Y_{t}-P_{t}^{R}R_{t}-\left[1+\tau_{t}^{L}\right]w_{t}L_{t}\\
\\
-\tau_{t}^{K}P_{t}^{I}K_{t-1}-T_{t}\\
\\
-r_{t}^{D}\mu_{t-1}^{D}P_{t-1}^{I}K_{t-1}
\end{array}\right)\\
\\
 & -P_{t}^{I}I_{t}+\tau_{t}^{c}\left(\delta_{t}^{Tax0}P_{t}^{I}I_{t}+\delta_{t}^{Tax}K_{t-1}^{Tax}\right)+\mu_{t}^{D}P_{t}^{I}K_{t}-\mu_{t-1}^{D}P_{t-1}^{I}K_{t-1}\\
\\
 & +q_{t}\left(\left[1-\delta_{t}\right]K_{t-1}+I_{t}-K_{t}\right)\\
\\
 & +q_{t}^{Tax}\left(\left[1-\delta_{t}^{Tax}\right]K_{t-1}^{Tax}+\left(\lambda_{t}^{Tax}-\delta_{t}^{Tax0}\right)P_{t}^{I}I_{t}-K_{t}^{Tax}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where net output 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=A_{t}\left[KELBR\left(u_{iM,t}K_{iM,t-1},E_{t},L_{t},u_{iB,t}K_{iB,t-1},R_{t}\right)-AC_{t}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To properly locate the elements in the CES tree above, the production function
 
\begin_inset Formula $KELBR$
\end_inset

 here corresponds to the top of the tree and has the associated CES price
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{KELBR}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimization price is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{t}=\frac{P_{t}^{KELBR}}{A_{t}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first block of the surplus expression in curved brackets lists elements
 affected by corporate taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{c}$
\end_inset

.
 It contains net output, minus expenses on intermediate goods and on labor
 costs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{K}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{L}$
\end_inset

 are net input taxes (such as property taxes, vehicle taxes, or payroll
 subsidies).
 Finally there are lump sum taxes 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 and interest payments on debt 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}^{D}$
\end_inset

, all of which reduce the taxable income (corporate tax) generated by the
 firm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After these we have the nominal investment cost 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{I}I_{t}$
\end_inset

, the value of the tax deduction from capital depreciation, revenues (expenses)
 from increases (reductions) in corporate debt, and finally, the Lagrange
 multiplier (Tobin's q) and its attached law of motion for capital (the
 standard one), and the Lagrange multiplier and its attached law of motion
 for tax (or book) value capital.
 The tax value of capital is the nominal object, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}^{Tax}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
First-order conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discount factor between time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t+1}=\frac{1}{1+r_{t+1}}$
\end_inset

.
 The required rate of return, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

, is taken as given by the firm and may vary across sectors if investors
 demand different risk premia to hold equity in different sector.
 In subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Costly External Finance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we discuss the introduction of costly external finance in the firm's problem,
 modeled so that its effect is contained in an augmented discount factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal choice of labor is detailed in the labor market chapter.
 The first-order condition for capital utilization is discussed in section
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Factor-utilization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) below.
 The first-order conditions for energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}$
\end_inset

, and intermediate goods, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}$
\end_inset

, are simply 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}^{KE}\frac{\partial KE_{t}}{\partial E_{t}}=P_{t}^{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}\frac{\partial KELBR_{t}}{\partial R_{t}}=P_{t}^{R}$
\end_inset

 and, since this optimization is static, it is already obtained in the CES
 cost minimization problem.
 The first-order condition for investment, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{t}$
\end_inset

, which isolates Tobin's q, is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{t}=P_{t}^{I}\left(1-\tau_{t}^{c}\delta_{t}^{Tax0}-\left(\lambda_{t}^{Tax}-\delta_{t}^{Tax0}\right)q_{t}^{Tax}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order condition for the book/tax value of capital, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}^{Tax}$
\end_inset

 , is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{t}^{Tax}=\beta_{t+1}\tau_{t+1}^{c}\delta_{t+1}^{Tax}+\beta_{t+1}\left(1-\delta_{t+1}^{Tax}\right)q_{t+1}^{Tax}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{t}^{Tax}$
\end_inset

 is the tax deductible depreciation rate, 
