\begin_layout Subsection
Firm investments with costly external finance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Costly External Finance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following we detail a reduced form way of modeling costly external
 finance through the firm's discount factor.
 Besides financial frictions being a realistic feature of the theory of
 the firm, they help generate pro-cyclical investment in line with data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
An illustrative example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest model of the firm abstracts from costly external finance.
 The firm has free access to funds at an exogenous rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

, which is the discount rate of its cash flows, and which is the required
 rate of return demanded by all investors.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There are also no conflicts of interest between management and ownership,
 and no issues of corporate control.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A simple illustration of this model is the one variable example where the
 capital stock obeys the standard law of motion 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}=\left(1-\delta\right)K_{t-1}+I_{t}$
\end_inset

, and profits are given by revenues minus investment costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}=Y\left(K_{t-1}\right)-P_{t}^{I}I_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The unconstrained optimal choice of capital obeys
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\pi_{t}}{\partial K_{t}}+\beta_{t+1}\frac{\partial\pi_{t+1}}{\partial K_{t}}=0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t+1}=1/(1+r_{t+1})$
\end_inset

 is the discount factor which is exogenous to the firm and is not affected
 by how much the firm chooses to invest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this is an incomplete model since financing the firm's activity
 is a complex process.
 When firms finance their activity, the immediate source of funds is retained
 earnings or internal finance.
 This is often not enough and firms also interact with banks, issue corporate
 debt, and raise or buy back equity.
 One common characteristic of all sources of outside finance is that it
 is costly and therefore, we want to extend the model of the firm by defining
 this cost.
 Before that, in order for costly external finance to matter the firm must
 be in need of funds: it must be constrained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest model of costly outside finance adds a constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}\geq\bar{\pi}$
\end_inset

.
 Outside finance beyond this threshold is infinitely costly.
 With a Lagrange multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 the optimal decision obeys
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\pi_{t}}{\partial K_{t}}+\left[\beta_{t+1}\frac{1+\xi_{t+1}}{1+\xi_{t}}\right]\frac{\partial\pi_{t+1}}{\partial K_{t}}=0
\]

\end_inset

where if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}<\bar{\pi}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}>0$
\end_inset

 (and large enough).
 The firm can raise cash freely up until the threshold and after that the
 cost of outside finance is prohibitive.
 The optimality condition shows that this financial friction is fully captured
 in the generalized discount factor.

\shape italic
 
\shape default
While this is not a general property of models of firm finance, we choose
 our model so that we have it.
 When the constraint binds, this generalized discount factor is lower (the
 future becomes less relevant).
 This is intuitive as the effect of costly external finance is to reduce
 investment.
 However, that is not the only effect of costly external finance on the
 firm.
 In fact, how this constraint moves is more interesting over the business
 cycle.
 Although the existence of costly external finance acts to 
\emph on
reduce
\emph default
 investment, as long as the constraint is normally binding what matters
 is how the constraint tightens and relaxes.
 These effects through the constraint help propagate the business cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In MAKRO we model the costs of external finance assuming that they generally
 bind.
 We do this by using a differentiable cost function as in Gomes (2001) as
 a flexible way of modeling the above Lagrange multiplier.
 His model is as follows.
 Dividends are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{t}=\pi_{t}-\xi\left(m_{t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 having value zero for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq0$
\end_inset

 and a positive increasing function for 
\begin_inset Formula $m>0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}=-\pi_{t}=P_{t}^{I}I_{t}-Y_{t}$
\end_inset

, and it is easy to verify that it yields the same first-order condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\pi_{t}}{\partial K_{t}}+\left[\beta_{t+1}\frac{1+\frac{\partial\xi_{t+1}}{\partial m_{t+1}}}{1+\frac{\partial\xi_{t}}{\partial m_{t}}}\right]\frac{\partial\pi_{t+1}}{\partial K_{t}}=0
\]

\end_inset

where the Lagrange multipliers are replaced with the derivatives of the
 cost function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The financial constraint in MAKRO
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-Financial-Constraint"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firm maximizes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}=m_{t}-\xi_{t}+\beta_{t+1}V_{t+1}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the free cash flow of the firm (excluding financial assets).
 The positive valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}\equiv\xi\left(m_{t}-\overline{m}_{t}\right)\ge0$
\end_inset

 models the cost of financial frictions.
 The first-order condition with respect to a given input 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial m_{t}}{\partial X_{t}}+\hat{\beta}_{t+1}\frac{\partial m_{t+1}}{\partial X_{t}}=0
\]

\end_inset

where the augmented discount factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\beta}_{t+1}=\beta_{t+1}\frac{1-\partial\xi_{t+1}/\partial m_{t+1}}{1-\partial\xi_{t}/\partial m_{t}}
\]

\end_inset

We can rewrite the augmented discount factor as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}_{t+1}=1/(1+r_{t+1}+r_{t+1}^{p}+r_{t+1}^{\xi})$
\end_inset

 by defining a premium 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t+1}^{\xi}$
\end_inset

 associated with the financial constraint.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We specify the financial friction function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 as a differentiable symmetric function with derivative given by the hyperbolic
 tangent function
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $tanh(x)=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(e^{x}-e^{-x}\right)/\left(e^{x}+e^{-x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is well defined for the entire support of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This makes the primitive function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 a two-sided penalty function for missing profit targets and can be viewed
 as the cost of issuing 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m_{t}<\overline{m}_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 or re-purchasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(m_{t}>\overline{m}_{t}\right)$
\end_inset

 equity.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\xi_{t}}{\partial m_{t}}\equiv\mu\tanh\left(\kappa\left[m_{t}-\overline{m}_{t}\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{m_{t}\rightarrow\infty}\partial\xi_{t}/\partial m_{t}=\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{m_{t}\rightarrow-\infty}\partial\xi_{t}/\partial m_{t}=-\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Numerically, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=2\%$
\end_inset

 the firm pays a 2 pct.
 fee for outside finance (
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}<\overline{m}_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa>0$
\end_inset

 controls the slope of the derivative around 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{t}-\overline{m}_{t}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
