\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 is sector specific with sector subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, and is approximately homogeneous if 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{m}_{s,t}=0$
\end_inset

 and with high enough 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

.
 To preserve long run homogeneity with a free cash flow target different
 from zero we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{m}_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 endogenously adjust as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{m}_{s,t}=\gamma\overline{m}_{s,t-1}+\left(1-\gamma\right)m_{s,t}-\epsilon_{s,t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 controls the speed of adjustment and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 is calibrated to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{m}_{s,t}=m_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 in the baseline forecast.
 We calibrate 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{s,t}=\frac{\hat{\kappa}}{K_{s,t}}$
\end_inset

 (other measures of sector size can be used) to ensure similar behavior
 across sectors.
 For strict homogeneity 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 would need to endogenously adapt to changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{s,t}$
\end_inset

, but this is unlikely to matter in practice as 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{s,t}-\overline{m}_{s,t}$
\end_inset

 converges to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful to define the 'habit adjusted' free cash flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{m}_{s,t}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{m}_{s,t}\equiv m_{s,t}-\overline{m}_{s,t}=\gamma\left[m_{s,t}-m_{s,t-1}+\hat{m}_{s,t-1}\right]+\epsilon_{s,t}
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging the augmented discount factor we get an expression for the discount
 rate premium associated with the financial constraint
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{s,t+1}^{\xi}=\left[1+r_{t+1}+r_{t+1}^{p}\right]\left[\frac{1-\mu_{s}\tanh\left(\kappa_{s}\hat{m}_{s,t}\right)}{1-\mu_{s}\tanh\left(\kappa_{s}\hat{m}_{s,t+1}\right)}-1\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Acceleration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The financial constraint model we use is closer to the Gomes (2001) model
 than to collateral acceleration models such as Bernanke and Gertler (1989).
 The factors relaxing the constraint in good times come from the expansion
 of revenues as prices increase and from the increased production ability
 as capital accumulates.
 There is no additional contribution from an improvement in collateral values
 or from any additional relaxation of the constraint from a goodwill effect
 arising from extra revenues.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These mechanisms are discussed in recent work.
 See Lian and Ma (2020) and Drechsel (2021) and references therein.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Finance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Finance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Production firms hold and manage liquid assets (cash, credit lines, liquid
 assets) since, due to financial frictions, cash inside the firm is not
 identical to cash outside it.
 These frictions are currently modeled parsimoniously in the production
 model and so the presence of financial assets in the firm's balance sheet
 is dealt with in reduced form and separated from the firm's optimization
 problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Financial services also account for a significant share of total services.
 We do not have a model of the financial firm, and therefore there is no
 theory of endogenous optimal decision making for these agents, but we do
 have basic principles of financial arbitrage which we apply to include
 financial stocks and flows in the MAKRO model.
 These assets must be adequately accounted for in order to fit the national
 accounts data (Nationalregnskabet) and make up a separate entity from productio
n firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data contains both financial and production components of firm valuation.
 Financial assets are valued at current market price
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The value of cash and other low-return instruments outside the firm would
 be higher than the discounted nominal value of their returns inside the
 firm.
 This is corrected by their convenience yield: this is the exact difference
 between the nominal yield the asset generates and the required rate on
 equity.
 Keynes used the idea of convenience yield in his money demand function.
 See also Del Negro et al.
 (2017), Safety, Liquidity, and the Natural rate of Interest, Brookings
 Papers, Spring 2017.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We now provide a brief introduction to financial valuation and accounting.
 More detailed descriptions are contained in the appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Valuation algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We divide the value of the firm, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

, into two separate objects: 1) The value of the main operations of the
 firm 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{x}$
\end_inset

, and 2) the value of net financial assets not related to the main operations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}^{x}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}=V_{t}^{x}+B_{t}^{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value of operations is the discounted value of the cash flows that result
 from the endogenous optimal decisions of the firm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}^{x}=\frac{\pi_{t+1}+V_{t+1}^{x}}{1+r_{t+1}^{E}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The required return on equity is the sum of the bond rate and an equity
 risk premium and differs from the discount rate used by the firm in its
 optimal production decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Net financial assets consist of a several asset classes (index 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) and two types of debt (index 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 for liabilities).
 All the portfolio components are valued at their market price.
 For example, financial firms hold a large number of mortgage bonds that
 we value at their market price rather than discounting their associated
 interest rate payments with the required return on equity.
 The debt associated with capital, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{t}^{D}P_{t}^{I}K_{t}$
\end_inset

, is included in the value of main operations and is therefore not included
 in net financial assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{t}^{x}=\underbrace{\sum_{A}B_{A,t}}_{\text{financial assets}}-\left[\underbrace{\sum_{L}B_{L,t}}_{\text{total debt}}-\underbrace{\mu_{t}^{D}P_{t}^{I}K_{t}}_{\text{debt from operations}}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the firm holds financial assets proportional to the value
 of their main operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{t}^{x}=\left(\sum_{A}\mu_{A,t}^{B}-\sum_{L}\mu_{L,t}^{B}\right)V_{t}^{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now write a budget constraint of the firm which ties together net
 financial assets with the cash flow from main operations, dividends paid
 and finally revenue from new equity issues (buybacks if negative):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{t}^{x}=\left(1+\left[1-\tau_{t}^{c}\right]r_{t}^{Bx}\right)B_{t-1}^{x}+\pi_{t}-div_{t}+issues_{t}+\underbrace{\epsilon_{t}}_{\text{other transfers}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}^{Bx}$
\end_inset

 is the rate return on net financial assets before taxes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that firms follow a constant dividend rate policy such that dividends
 are proportional to the total value of shares,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
div_{t}=r_{t}^{div}V_{t-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
implying equity issues are endogenous and determined residually by the budget
 constraint.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The separation between dividends and equity issuance has minor tax implications,
 but is primarily necessary in order to match national accounting data.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The change in share price is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{t}^{omv}=\frac{V_{t}-issues_{t}}{V_{t-1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the rate of return on equity 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r^{div}+r^{omv}\right)$
\end_inset

 is unaffected by the dividend policy and equity issuance.
 I.e., if the firm issues equities and uses the money to buy financial assets,
 the value of shares including financial assets, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

, increases by exactly the same amount and share prices do not change.
 Similarly, when the firm pays dividends, their value decreases by the same
 amount.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Financial accounting terms and corporate taxes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to define the scope of corporate taxation 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{c}$
\end_inset

 we make a detour to discuss how EBITDA (Earnings Before Interests, Taxes,
 Depreciation and Amortization) , and how EBT (Earnings Before Tax), translate
 into the income the cash flow from main operations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, (which we used in the dynamic optimization problem of the firm):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pi_{t} & =\underbrace{P_{t}Y_{t}-P_{t}^{R}R_{t}-\left[1+\tau_{t}^{L}\right]w_{t}L_{t}-\tau_{t}^{K}P_{t}^{I}K_{t-1}-T_{t}}_{\text{EBITDA}}\\
\\
 & -P_{t}^{I}I_{t}+\underbrace{\mu_{t}^{D}P_{t}^{I}K_{t}-\left(1+r_{t}^{D}\right)\mu_{t-1}^{D}P_{t-1}^{I}K_{t-1}}_{\text{new debt without interest tax deduction}}\\
\\
 & -\tau_{t}^{c}\left[\underbrace{\text{EBITDA}_{t}^{x}-\delta_{t}^{Tax}K_{t-1}^{Tax}-r_{t}^{D}\mu_{t-1}^{D}P_{t-1}^{I}K_{t-1}}_{\text{EBT}^{x}}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\text{EBT}^{x}$
\end_inset

 consists of earnings before taxes 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 before income from net financial assets.
 To get the total tax base for corporate taxes we add the income from the
 net financial assets part of the firm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{EBT}_{t}=\text{EBT}^{x}+r_{t}^{Bx}B_{t-1}^{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

before taxes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in EBITDA and EBT refers to corporate taxes only and not production taxes.
 Net production taxes consist of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{L}$
\end_inset

 (payroll taxes and subsidies), 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{t}^{K}$
\end_inset

 (land and vehicle taxes) and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{t}$
\end_inset

 (other production taxes, which are treated as exogenous to the firm), which
 can all be considered part of the net prices of the firm's production inputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Special sector considerations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Special-sector-considerations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The extraction sector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The extractions sector consists of oil and gas and a small amount of gravel
 extraction.
 Output and prices from this sector are exogenous and based on forecasts
 from the Danish Energy Agency (Energistyrelsen).
 Given the exogenous output, production factors are endogenously chosen
 to minimize costs and modeled the same way as other sectors apart from
 the existence of an additional tax:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau_{\text{extraction},t}^{c}=\tau_{t}^{c}+\frac{y_{\text{extraction,}t}-y_{t}^{\text{\emph{gravel}}}}{y_{\text{extraction,}t}}\tau_{t}^{oil}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As both the price and domestic output quantity is exogenous, we scale the
 demand for domestic extraction output proportionally to match the supply.
 Demand for extraction imports is scaled inversely such that the total demand
 for extraction does not depend on the exogenized sector output.
 I.e., import and domestic production of extraction are perfect substitutes,
 and we allocate a share of domestic output to different types of demand
 and use imports to satisfy residual demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The housing sector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the national accounts, the housing sector produces housing services where
 the key input is a measure of the stock of houses.
 The sector includes both rental and privately owned housing and produces
 a homogeneous good priced at the rental value of housing.
 The rent value of owner-occupied housing is imputed based on rents of comparabl
e rental housing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model, we have an endogenous decision by households on owner-occupied
 housing while rental housing enters the household problem exogenously.
 As we do not (yet) model the rental market, both consumption and production
 of rental housing are exogenous.
 The housing stock available for rent is exogenous and assumed to depend
 on government-supported rental building projects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that the rental part of housing is exogenous, we need to decouple
 it from owner-occupied housing.
 In order to achieve this separation, we model the production of housing
 services using a Leontief production function.
 The main input is the existing stock of housing (structures) and there
 is no input of capital equipment.
 Note that this measure of housing stock excludes land, and therefore it
 is not the housing measure, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, described in the household chapter.
 In the data, this sector accounts for services such as housing maintenance
 
\begin_inset Formula $(\approx15\%)$
\end_inset

, which involves labor and intermediate inputs, and other (mainly financial)
 services 
\begin_inset Formula $(\approx10\%)$
\end_inset

, and for that reason it is organized as a production sector within the
 input/output structure of the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These three inputs, structures, labor, and intermediate goods, generate
 output through a Leontief production function.
 The consequence is that output, employment, and intermediate goods are
 proportional to the capital stock measure.
 Unlike production in the other private sectors, there are no adjustment
 costs to capital, and therefore, net and gross production are the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since everything is proportional to capital, we can separate all inputs
 and output in proportion to the fraction of structures that are owner-occupied
 housing (described as â€œbricksâ€ in the household chapter) and the fraction
 which is rental housing.
 This is equivalent to assuming separate but identical Leontief production
 technologies for owner-occupied and rental housing, so they have equal
 amounts of intermediate goods and labor in proportion to their respective
 building capital stock.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the rental part of the data is separated, we calculate how it behaves
 in existing data and forecast its use of resources in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Formalizing the problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Net output 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 uses energy 
\begin_inset Formula $(E)$
\end_inset

, labor 
\begin_inset Formula $(L)$
\end_inset

, structures 
\begin_inset Formula $(K_{iB})$
\end_inset

, and intermediate goods 
\begin_inset Formula $(R)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=A_{t}\cdot KELBR_{t}\left(E_{t},L_{t},K_{iB,t-1},R_{t}\right)=A_{t}\cdot\min\left(\frac{\phi_{iB}}{\phi_{R}}R_{t},\min\left(\phi_{iB}K_{iB,t-1},\min\left(\frac{\phi_{iB}}{\phi_{L}}L_{t},\frac{\phi_{iB}}{\phi_{L}}E_{t}\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

and the Leontief function implies the optimality conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $KELBR_{t}=\phi_{iB}K_{iB,t-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}=\phi_{E}K_{iB,t-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}=\phi_{L}K_{iB,t-1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{t}=\phi_{R}K_{iB,t-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capital stock 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{iB,t}$
\end_inset

 (here, the total stock of structures or â€œbricksâ€), and the associated investmen
ts, are the sum of owner-occupied and rental housing.
 The owner-occupied housing part is endogenous, while the rental part is
 an exogenous projection.
 The owned housing part of this stock is described in the household chapter
 in the section covering the housing intermediary.
 Output, employment, and the use of intermediate inputs are endogenous,
 but all of them are proportional to the stock due to the Leontief production
 function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Link to the household problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we decouple rental housing from owned housing, we introduce them differently
 in the household problem.
 The rental housing coming out of this sector is added exogenously to the
 household's budget constraint, while owner-occupied housing is an optimal
 decision.
 Owner-occupied housing is bought from an intermediary that takes a flow
 product from the construction sector, puts it on a plot of land, and sells
 the final combined good (bricks and land) to the household.
 Rental housing does not explicitly contain land.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Land is introduced in MAKRO in this specific way to improve house prices'
 modeling.
 The user cost of owner-occupied housing includes the effect of the price
 of land.
 Currently, land is not included in any other product or sector.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If we remove the value added of land from the house bought by households,
 we have a stock equivalent to the rental housing capital, and the sum of
 the two stocks match the data from the housing services sector described
 here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the problem of the household we can find in the budget constraint a term
 which accounts for expenses with housing maintenance, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}P_{t-1}^{D}D_{a-1,t-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The factor 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 in this term is taken as given by the household and is the fraction of
 the energy, labor and intermediate goods costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[P_{t}^{E}\phi_{E}+P_{t}^{L}\phi_{L}+P_{t}^{R}\phi_{R}\right]$
\end_inset

 we have in the problem above which is allocated to owner-occupied housing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the household owns the stock of owner-occupied housing and pays
 directly for its maintenance costs.
 Therefore only the fraction of sector profits corresponding to rental housing
 can be allocated through the ownership of the firm in the household portfolio,
 controlling for the fact that households consume an exogenous amount of
 rental housing and pay rent on it.
\end_layout

